<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="52" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="53.[813,1456,1090,1432]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">
DISTRIBUTION, ECOLOGY AND CONSERVATION STATUS. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Xylopia carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[945,1025,1117,1140]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is known from only two collections, both from northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1004,1121,1143,1167]" name="Madagascar" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
in humid forest at elevations up to 200 meters, one collection on sand (
<figureCitation box="[1198,1267,1170,1194]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="82.[132,143,1799,1817]" captionTargetBox="[134,1453,214,1759]" captionTargetId="figure@82.[458,797,717,1245]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIG. 28. — Distributions of Xylopia ambanjensis Cavaco &amp; Keraudren, X. anomala, sp. nov., X. australis, sp.nov., X.beananensis Cavaco &amp; Keraudren, X. bemarivensis Diels,X.buxifolia Baill., X.capuronii Cavaco &amp; Keraudren,X. carinata, sp. nov., X. danguyella Ghesq. ex Cavaco &amp; Keraudren, X. dielsii Cavaco &amp; Keraudren, X. fananehanensis Cavaco &amp; Keraudren, and X. flexuosa Diels on Madagascar." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3877272" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3877272/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). It is possible that 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" box="[813,921,1197,1220]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[813,921,1197,1220]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">X. carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[935,1015,1197,1220]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is a habitat specialist, as the type specimen was collected from sublittoral forest on sand, to which a number of other 
<collectingCountry box="[902,1019,1249,1273]" name="Madagascar" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName box="[1026,1097,1249,1273]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1097,1249,1273]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Xylopia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species appear to be restricted, but the 
<typeStatus box="[850,933,1276,1300]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">paratype</typeStatus>
specimen label does not give any habitat information and was collected some distance inland. The collections, both with flowers only, were collected in March and in October. The AOO of 
<quantity box="[838,888,1355,1379]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="km" value="8.0">8 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[888,897,1355,1372]" fontSize="7" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">2</superScript>
and its known occurrence at only two localities make this a species of conservation concern, and it is given a preliminary assessment of Endangered (
<tableCitation box="[1062,1135,1408,1432]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="18.[214,225,221,239]" captionText="TABLE 2. — Preliminary and published conservation assessments for Madagascar and Mascarene Xylopia species.Abbreviations:CR, Critically Endangered; D, based on IUCN Criterion D; DD, Data Deficient; EN, Endangered; VU, Vulnerable. Sources: 1, Page 1998a; 2, Lantoarisoa 2015; 3, Callmander et al. 2009; 4, Page 1998b; 5, Page 1998c. *, See Discussion under X. flexuosa Diels." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/9DAB663AFFEFFFFEFF0A52C5370AFEBF" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" tableUuid="9DAB663AFFEFFFFEFF0A52C5370AFEBF">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="55" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="53.[813,1456,1460,1615]" box="[813,952,1460,1486]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[813,1456,1460,1615]" box="[813,1026,1492,1519]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,858,1492,1518]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Tree</emphasis>
up to 
<quantity box="[926,980,1493,1519]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="m" value="20.0">20 m</quantity>
tall.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[813,1456,1460,1615]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,875,1556,1582]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Twigs</emphasis>
yellowish brown-pubescent, the hairs 
<quantity box="[1270,1396,1556,1583]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="0.3" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.1">0.1-0.5 mm</quantity>
long, eventually glabrate; nodes with one or often two axillary branches.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[813,1455,1652,2030]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,885,1652,1678]" pageId="53" pageNumber="52">Leaves</emphasis>
with larger blades 
<quantity box="[1086,1204,1652,1679]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.6" metricValueMax="9.7" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="cm" value="8.6" valueMax="9.7" valueMin="7.5">7.5-9.7 cm</quantity>
long, 2.6-4.0 cm wide, subcoriaceous, discolorous, olive-gray to dark brown adaxially, brown abaxially, oblong to oblong-elliptic, apex acute to acuminate, the acumen 
<quantity box="[1062,1148,1748,1775]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="6.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="5.0">5-8 mm</quantity>
long, base broadly cuneate to rounded, short-decurrent on petiole, margin recurved, pubescent along midrib but otherwise glabrous adaxially, sparsely appressed-pubescent, hairs densest on the midrib abaxially; midrib concolorous or darkened toward base adaxially, secondary veins brochidodromous, 11-15 per side, diverging at 60-70° from midrib, these and higher-order veins slightly raised to indistinct on both surfaces; petiole 
<quantity box="[1302,1392,1971,1998]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="52" unit="mm" value="6.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="4.0">4-8 mm</quantity>
long, canaliculate to semi-terete, wrinkled, pubescent.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3877252" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3877252" box="[253,1336,2009,2028]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3877252/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="53" startId="54.[253,264,2009,2027]" targetBox="[152,1455,216,1986]" targetPageId="54">
<paragraph box="[253,1336,2009,2028]" pageId="54" pageNumber="53">
FIG. 18. — Plate showing illustration of 
<emphasis box="[578,719,2009,2027]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="53">Xylopia capuronii</emphasis>
Cavaco &amp; Keraudren (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[907,941,2009,2028]" pageId="54" pageNumber="53">A -D</emphasis>
), reproduced from 
<bibRefCitation author="CAVACO A. &amp; KERAUDREN M." box="[1101,1332,2009,2027]" pageId="54" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 24" refId="ref88020" refString="CAVACO A. &amp; KERAUDREN M. 1958. - 78 e Famille: Annonacees, in HUMBERT H. (ed.), Flore de Madagascar et des Comores. Typographie Firmin-Didot et Cie, Paris: 1 - 109 + pl. 1 - 24. https: // biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 9258792" type="book chapter" year="1958">Cavaco &amp; Keraudren (1958)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,217,435]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,285,217,243]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Inflorescences</emphasis>
axillary or from axils of fallen leaves, occasionally pseudoterminal from the abortion of the terminal bud, 1-2-flowered, not pedunculate, yellowish brown-pubescent; pedicels 
<quantity box="[224,367,313,340]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.3" metricValueMax="12.1" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="7.3" valueMax="12.1" valueMin="2.5">2.5-12.1 mm</quantity>
long, 1.0- 
<quantity box="[478,564,313,339]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
thick; bracts 2, one attached near pedicel midpoint and caducous, the other just proximal to the sepals and persistent, 
<quantity box="[583,713,377,403]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" metricValueMax="4.9" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="4.1" valueMax="4.9" valueMin="3.3">3.3-4.9 mm</quantity>
long, broadly ovate to semicircular; buds lanceolate, apex acute.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,776,471,563]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,197,472,498]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Sepals</emphasis>
erect to spreading at anthesis, ¼-1/3-connate, 
<quantity box="[652,775,472,499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="5.0" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.5">4.5-5.5 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[196,306,504,531]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.3" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="4.6" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="5.3" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.6">4.6-6 mm</quantity>
wide, coriaceous to slightly fleshy, broadly ovate, apex acute to obtuse, densely brown-pubescent abaxially.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,599,977]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,193,599,625]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Petals</emphasis>
yellowish 
<emphasis box="[299,365,601,626]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">in vivo</emphasis>
; outer petals probably slightly spreading at anthesis, 
<quantity box="[260,376,632,659]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="20.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="16.0">16-25 mm</quantity>
long, 5.2-6.0 mm wide at base, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.7" valueMin="2.9">2.9- 3.7 mm</quantity>
wide at midpoint, slightly fleshy, lanceolate, keeled on apical 1/2 but otherwise flat adaxially, keeled abaxially, apex acute to obtuse, densely puberulent except for the glabrous base adaxially, velutinous abaxially; inner petals probably with apices spreading at anthesis, 
<quantity box="[450,590,791,818]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3599999999999999" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.02" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="13.6" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="10.2">10.2-17 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[663,775,791,818]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.65" metricValueMax="4.3" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="3.65" valueMax="4.3" valueMin="3.0">3-4.3 mm</quantity>
wide at base, 
<quantity box="[280,411,823,850]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.2">1.2-1.7 mm</quantity>
wide at midpoint, slightly fleshy, lanceolate, keeled on apical 1/2 adaxially, sharply keeled abaxially, apex acute, base concave with undifferentiated or slightly thickened margin, densely puberulent except for glabrous base on both surfaces.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,1014,1295]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,227,1014,1040]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Stamens</emphasis>
120-200; fertile stamens 
<quantity box="[520,655,1015,1041]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.55" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.3">1.3-1.8 mm</quantity>
long, narrowly oblong, anther connective apex 
<emphasis box="[537,554,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">c.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[560,645,1046,1073]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
long, hemispherical, overhanging anther thecae, long-papillate, anthers 7-9-locellate, filament 
<quantity box="[381,514,1110,1137]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="0.35" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.2">0.2-0.5 mm</quantity>
long; outer staminodes 
<quantity box="[132,261,1142,1169]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.7">1.7-1.8 mm</quantity>
long, clavate, apex obtuse, truncate, or emarginate; inner staminodes 
<quantity box="[357,481,1174,1200]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5499999999999998" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.5499999999999998" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.4">1.4-1.7 mm</quantity>
long, narrowly oblong, apex truncate to obtuse; staminal cone 1.3-3.0 mm in diameter, 
<quantity box="[132,262,1238,1264]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.05" valueMax="1.3" valueMin="0.8">0.8-1.3 mm</quantity>
high, concealing all but apical 1/3 of ovaries, rim irregularly laciniate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,1333,1424]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,215,1333,1359]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Carpels</emphasis>
6-17; ovaries 
<emphasis box="[368,385,1334,1359]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">c.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[391,521,1333,1360]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="1.3" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="0.8">0.8-1.8 mm</quantity>
long, narrowly oblong, pubescent, stigmas connivent, 
<quantity box="[472,605,1365,1392]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" metricValueMax="3.2" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" unit="mm" value="2.8" valueMax="3.2" valueMin="2.4">2.4-3.2 mm</quantity>
long, narrowly clavate, glabrous or hairy at the apices.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,426,1460,1487]" box="[132,426,1460,1487]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,309,1460,1486]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Fruits and seeds</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="55" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,1524,2030]" box="[132,206,1524,1550]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">NOTES</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,1524,2030]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
The keel on the abaxial surface of the outer petals, for which 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" box="[132,303,1588,1614]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[132,303,1588,1614]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Xylopia carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[319,405,1589,1615]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is named, is conspicuous in both of the collections. In the 
<typeStatus box="[410,456,1621,1647]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
collection some flowers arise at the proximal nodes of an expanding axillary shoot from which the subtending leaves have precociously fallen, giving the appearance of a multi-flowered inflorescence. 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Xylopia carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[234,320,1748,1774]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is a member of the group of 
<collectingCountry box="[648,775,1748,1774]" name="Madagascar" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName box="[132,212,1780,1806]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[132,212,1780,1806]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Xylopia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with clavate stigmas, and, as noted in the diagnosis, is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavaco &amp; Keraudren" authorityYear="1956" box="[446,577,1812,1837]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="capuronii">
<emphasis box="[446,577,1812,1837]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">X. capuronii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" box="[635,767,1812,1838]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lokobensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[635,767,1812,1838]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">X. lokobensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[132,214,1844,1870]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The 
<typeStatus box="[267,313,1844,1870]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
specimen was determined by Keraudren as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cavaco &amp; Keraudren" authorityYear="1957" box="[132,307,1875,1901]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ghesquiereana">
<emphasis box="[132,307,1875,1901]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">X. ghesquiereana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it does not have the linear petals and barbate leaf midrib and leaf margins found in that species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[132,775,1524,2030]" lastBlockId="55.[813,1456,217,626]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">
Fruits and seeds are not known for this species. However, two 
<taxonomicName box="[236,314,1971,1997]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[236,314,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Xylopia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collections with fruits, 
<emphasis box="[570,774,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Capuron 18178 SF</emphasis>
(P[P01986948, P01986949]) from Rantolava, NW de Tam- polo – Fénérive, 
<date box="[997,1112,217,244]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" value="1957-09-01">1.IX.1957</date>
, and 
<emphasis box="[1172,1455,217,244]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Service Forestier 15268-SF</emphasis>
(P[P01986952]), Manakara, 
<date box="[1136,1286,249,276]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" value="1955-08-27">27.VIII.1955</date>
, are tentatively placed here, as the leaves, while more chartaceous, are similar in size and indument to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Johnson &amp; Murray, 2020" authorityName="D. M. Johnson &amp; N. A. Murray" authorityYear="2020" box="[1181,1300,314,339]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Annonaceae" genus="Xylopia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Magnoliales" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carinata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1181,1300,314,339]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">X. carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1315,1402,313,339]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and the specimens were both collected from coastal locations in the general area of the 
<typeStatus box="[1069,1116,377,403]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
locality. The collection 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Service Forestier 15268-SF</emphasis>
is further noteworthy in including a mass of monocarps that have dehisced. The monocarps of both specimens are ellipsoid and sparsely pubescent. A photograph posted on iNaturalist in 2017, taken in the Analalava Nature Preserve near the 
<typeStatus box="[1087,1134,537,563]" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">type</typeStatus>
locality, shows a similar mass of dehisced monocarps, as well as an orange sarcotesta on the seeds (
<figureCitation box="[925,1010,600,626]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="8.[132,143,1805,1823]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1776]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[698,1267,751,1325]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIG. 2. — Fruits and seeds of Madagascar Xylopia L. species: A, fruits of X. retusa, sp. nov., showing at left a dehiscent monocarp with one seed covered by an orange sarcotesta (Rabenantoandro et al. 1249); B, fruit of X. perrieri Diels, one monocarp dehiscing to reveal barely visible seed with light green sarcotesta (Antilahimena 7187); C, dehiscing monocarps of a Xylopia sp., possibly X. carinata, sp. nov., with orange sarcotesta of seeds visible; D, fruit of X. bemarivensis Diels, with one dehiscing monocarp and seed with orange sarcotesta visible (Ranirison PR 808); E, immature fruit of X. flexuosa Diels, showing the elongate monocarp characteristic of species in sect. Xylopia (Rakotovao 4687); F, fruit of X. humblotiana Baill., with one dehisced monocarp and black seeds with white arils visible (Rakotovao 4886); G, fruits of X. sclerophylla, sp. nov.; monocarp at lower right is probably recently dehisced because green sarcotesta of seed is fully intact (Nusbaumer LN 943); H, dehisced monocarp of X. sclerophylla, sp. nov., at a slightly later stage, showing the sarcotesta collapsing and losing its color (Nusbaumer LN 943). Photos: A, P. P. Lowry II; B, P. Antilahimena; C, J. Tan; D, P. Ranirison (© Conservatoire et Jardin botaniques de la Ville de Genève); E, F, C. Rakotovao; G, H, by L. Nusbaumer (© Conservatoire et Jardin botaniques de la Ville de Genève). A, B, D, E, F, used under the terms of the Creative Commons license for Tropicos,the botanical information system at the Missouri Botanical Garden; C, used under the terms of the the Creative Commons license for iNaturalist." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3877220" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3877220/files/figure.png" pageId="55" pageNumber="54">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
